\subsection{The relatively free algebra}
Given an arbitrary class \ab{ùí¶} of \ab{ùëÜ}-algebras, we cannot expect that \T{X} belongs to \ab{ùí¶}.
%, so we say \T{X} is free \emph{for} \ab{ùí¶} (as opposed to free \emph{in} \ab{ùí¶}).
Indeed, there may be no free algebra in \ab{ùí¶}.
Nonetheless, it is always possible to construct an algebra that is free for \ab{ùí¶} and belongs to the class \af{S} (\af{P} \ab{ùí¶}).
Such an algebra is called a \defn{relatively free algebra over} \ab{X} (relative to \ab{ùí¶}).
There are several informal approaches to defining this algebra.
We now describe the approach on which our formal construction is based and then we present the formalization.

